node.text:
It has been a wonderful, fun, and memorable first week of school so far. There is a sense of happiness and gratitude that you can just FEEL.

Today they were working on I Am poems and some were working around the room and some were working with me and everything just felt so right.

I know not every day or week or month will be like this so I’m just enjoying it as it comes.

But also: I’m exhausted. Let’s be real. 😂

Are you back to school? Getting ready?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jill ❤️ Hello Fifth in Los Angeles, California. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
Tomorrow is our first day!

The desks are set, the copies are made, and we are READY to welcome a new group of fifth graders!

On their desks they have a card from last year’s class, as well as our first day maze (link in profile). There’s a mechanical pencil, a name tag, and a sticky note that we will use after we read our first picture book together (The Day You Begin).

Here’s to a great year! ❤️

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jill ❤️ Hello Fifth in Los Angeles, California.

node.text:
We start with kids tomorrow and we start the 40 book challenge just a few days after that.

On day one, they choose a novel from our library because I want them to have a book in their hands. As we learn about the challenge and dive into genre, their selections might change but it’s really important to me that they leave after the first day with a book they’ve chosen.

Book bins are from Target and the genre labels are from @literacyforbigkids. Link in profile to read more about our class library.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jill ❤️ Hello Fifth in Los Angeles, California. May be an image of indoor and office.

node.text:
It took some creative DIY work to make this desk happen but I absolutely love the final product!

I took two of my old Ikea tables (Linnmon top, Adils legs) and formed an L-shape. I also ended up using bed risers and duct tape and maybe a zip tie or two. 😂 But, now I don’t have my back to anyone when I use the document camera so I call it a win.

Link in profile for the bulletin board lives above the desk.

I *think* the front of our room is ready (minus the tech stuff that I haven’t even attempted yet).

Today, I hung the fluorescent light covers and I really like how they muted the room in just the right way.

Link in profile for the ones I went with; they have magnets sewn in so they were pretty quick to hang!

I promise to do a tour soon. I’m in my old room but, of course, I made some changes. 😉 I always do.

node.text:
This Chihuly-inspired sculpture was created by my students years ago and traveled to several rooms with me.

I loved it so much and it was a great way to recycle water bottles. I’ll type below how we made ours.

🌟Gather plastic water bottles and dry them out.
🌟Use acrylic paints to cover the outside of each bottle (label removed).
🌟Let dry overnight.
🌟Make a snip in the bottom and cut a circle to remove the bottom/base. Then, cut a gentle spiral around the bottle, stopping at the top.
🌟Use hot glue to glue the bottles (lids on made it easier for me but we worked without them too) to a wreath form. I used a green styrofoam one from Dollar Tree.
🌟Weave some yarn around the form to make hangers. I hung ours from the ceiling.

Any questions? I’ll try and answer below!

I just added this to my back to school resource (so re-download if you already own!). Link in profile to grab!

How about some print-and-go learning mats that combine reading and grammar and multiplication?

The newest resource does just that and the math mazes are always my students’ favorite part!

This resource contains 20 mats and answer keys. If you like them, I’ll keep making more! We use them as morning work as kids enter but they could just as easily be used for early finishers or as partner work.
